msItem.title: Poem about knowledge and cunning
msItem.incipit: [i] verso Enforce your wyts sumwhat for to learen / A[...] you with coning for that ys seure / yf fortenne gane and pouerte apere / he that ys coning ys lyke to recouer
msItem.note: Full transcription attempted.
Added in a late 15th- or early 16th-century hand; not recorded in DIMEV.

msItem.title: A charm to protect a room from rats during the night
msItem.incipit: [iii] recto In the worship of [? our lord] god and our lady and sent Gerytreud A pater noster Aue [maria] and cred and that neit shall no rat do no harme in that Chamber where it is seyd
msItem.note: Full transcription with UV light. This previously untranscribed text concerns a charm that invokes St Gertrude of Nivelles for protection against rats.

msItem.title: Collection of medical recipes in the form of a treatise with cures for all ailments in the order of head to toe
msItem.rubric: 1r Here begynneth a tretys of al manere of infirmitees of mannys body bothe withinne as touchyng to phisyk and withoute as touching to surgerie from the croune of the heed to the sool of the foot and the remedies therwith if god wol and first we wol at heer of the hed how it shulde be norisshede and kepte etcaetera
msItem.incipit: 1r ffor to make heer growe: Take withien leues and sethe hem in oyle and hony and anoynte the heede
msItem.explicit: 52r Anoþer: Take clene whete and sethe it til it be broke and stampe it waterlees
msItem.note: The title Of all Maner of Infyrmytes has been added by a later hand.
See Mooney (1995), p. 133 for other copies.

msItem.title: The Dome of Uryne Compendium [Abbreviated Version]
msItem.rubric: 52v Ad discenendum vrinam humanam ab vrina mulieris et vrinam bestie ab vrina humana vel muliebri
msItem.incipit: 52v Thou shalt vnderstonde that if thee b eny trouble in mannys vryne that troublenes shewith in the myddes of the vryne and in a wommanys water it doth not so
msItem.explicit: 57r And if thou se ij. smale greynes in the seconde regioun or moo or lasse knytte vnto a smale skye it tokeneth renne in the breste and a wickede stomak and a badde lyuere and badde lunges etcaetera

msItem.title: The Governance of Signs
msItem.incipit: 57r It is for to wite that euery month in the yere the mone hath his course in þe xij sygnes in euery signe the mone is ij dais and an half almoost
msItem.explicit: 59r Thei be called good signes that be called sanguineus . And tho that ben malencolyous be called badde signes . And tho that ben coleryk . And fleumous . stonde in mene be war.
msItem.note: See Mooney (1995), p. 134 for other copies.

msItem.title: The Four Elements [Abbreviated Version]
msItem.incipit: 59r It is to vnderstonde that euery man is maad of iiij elementes that is to say . that euery man hath iiij. humours like to the iiij. elementes
msItem.explicit: 65v And fro ix. of the kloc before mydnyght til iij. of the kloc after mydnyght regnith flume that is cold and moist and so is that partie of the nyght and after begynneth blood to regne ayen

msItem.title: On the writing of weights and measures in recipes

msItem.incipit: 65v A pound is wryton thus li J.

msItem.title: Treatise on the signs of the zodiac and their influence over human activity
msItem.incipit: 65v-66r Aries hoot and drye whan the mone is vnder the signe of aries that wether that signe is mouable hoot and drye . Colerike of kynde of that fire . than it is good to make what thynge that longith to mevynge as forto bathene . to be late blood . that tyme is forto eschewen . forto touche the heed of man with iren . for why that signe Aries maketh the heed.
msItem.explicit: 69v And if eny man or womman be wounded in the feet whan the mone is vnderneth that signe vnnethe or euere he shal be couered

msItem.title: Prognostications based on the signs of the Zodiac
msItem.incipit: 69v Signum Aquarij dicitur . quia sanctus Johannes Baptista baptisatus fuit in flumine Jordani in mense Januarij quem habet Januarius . Qui nascitur in hoc signo negligens erit.
msItem.explicit: 70v Signum Capricorni dicitus . quia Dauid cum Golia pugnant in mense Decembri quem habet Cpricornius . Qui in hoc signo nascitur . diues et amabilis erit valde

msItem.title: Table of contents for the compendium of medicines (ff. 72r-83v)
msItem.rubric: 70v This table tellith of digestiues symple and compound of euery humoure that is to say of colere ffleume and malencolie
msItem.incipit: 70v-71r The first chapiter of medicyne symple digestiues of Coler and compouned
msItem.explicit: 72r The xxix. is of medicines symple kelynge the ioyntes and compound for the same

msItem.title: Compendium of medicines in 29 chapters
msItem.rubric: 72r-72v ffor soth somme goode frendes whiche trowed me to haue syght of konnynge praiden me to opene to hem in wrytynge shortly medicynes digestiues . and euacuatyes or voidyng symple and compound the whiche . leches commonly vseden . And for I sawe these thynges good . most to rude men and vnpractyke but the iust praier of hem meved me to wryte to hem. but it plesed to me that I speke first of medicyne dygestyes and euacuatyues of euery humour and in what membre thei ben inne. And after that I shal speke of medicynes removynge distraciam in what membre thei taken or forsaken . and medicynes confortynge membres . And of alle these thynges I shal say medicynes of auctours in her places . I wol begynne of digestyues ymple and compound
msItem.incipit: 72v Medicynes symple digestiues of coler ben these
msItem.explicit: 83v Compound for the same ben þese: Sirupus . rodoun . with medycynes colynge the reynes . the whiche ben afore seid

msItem.title: Collection of medical recipes in the form of a treatise
msItem.rubric: 85r Here folewen the Entraailes of man and medicynes also for certeyn parties of a mannys body
msItem.incipit: 85r The longe holdith the two ouer parties of the brest and it helith or couerith the herte the stomak is bitwene the ouer nesshe ribbes the litel wombe is vndernethe the stomak the gyser or the gyserne is in the right syde and he is sprad fro the nauell to the parte of the wombe and he ouerhelith the litel wombe
msItem.explicit: 111v-112r and thanne he shal haue esy seges but lete it not lye therto longe . for it wol thanne make hym to haue the flixe
msItem.note: This collection features an anatomical tract on ff. 85r-85v (eVK2 6894.00); and a regimen of health for the four seasons on ff. 86v-87v (eVK2 8173.00).

msItem.title: Five medical recipes
msItem.note: Five medical recipes for treating a bite wound from a dog, making a water for clearing the eyes, dropsy, a bloody nose, and sore eyes. These recipes immediately are seemingly continuous with the preceding collection of Latin medical recipes.

msItem.title: A medical recipes for 'burning of the legs'
msItem.incipit: 124v Take a payer of Tonges and hete them in the fyer tell they be hoote than take a pece of Bacon and let the hoote Tonges cause the Bacon to droppe in water than take a fether and take the droppyng and anoynte the sore therwith
msItem.note: Full transcription; added by a late 15th- or early 16th-century hand.
Mooney (1995) transcribes Scaldyng as Scaleyng, and translates it as scaling. However, this record assumes the gerund's fifth letter to be a d, which looks very similar to the scribe's round e.

msItem.title: Instructions for harnassing the magical properties of vervain
msItem.rubric: 124v To make a man gracius in all god werkys
msItem.incipit: 124v Take verueyn and gadre it in may or the sunne vp ryse and or þou take it vp go aboute it thries and euery tyme seye a pater noster and aue and in the takyn vp sey this orisun in nomine patris etcaetera herbam te colligo veruenam et quod dum te portauero vltrum omnia me amabus et plus me amando mihi concedas and take vp this herbe and bere it with the and thyn enmyes shull do the non harme and þou shall be gracius manyfole [sic] and yf þou wilt preue this take and cast it in a pond and the ffyssh shall gedre abute þat herbe
msItem.note: Full transcription; added by a late 15th- or early 16th-century hand.

msItem.title: A medical recipes for treating ague
msItem.rubric: 125r for the Agu a soueren medsyn
msItem.incipit: 125r Tak camomyll dawndelyon mors diabolle of evyryge a handfull a quarter of a handfull of wormot and halfe a handfull of mouse yere . boyle thes herbys yn possett ale fro iij quartes to a quart and a half than strayne [crossed out: th] the Possett alle and the erbys to gedyr than sethe hyt and bett the whytt of v new layd eges and put yt yn the possett alle when hyt begyn to sethe \and ?skim awey the eges/ as son as hyt dothe boylle tak hyt vp and strayne hyt and than geve the pacyent to drynk v sponfull at a tyme blod warme and drynk not afore by the space of a nower nodyr after by the space of iij owers
msItem.note: Full transcription; added by a late 15th- or early 16th-century hand.

msItem.title: A medical recipes for treating feet ailments
msItem.rubric: 125r Yf a man evs to parbrak yn the same dyses
msItem.incipit: 125r Tak a handfull of wormot a handfull of tanse a handfull of fetherfoy and broys them betwen your handes than mak ij bages of the breed and the lenthe of your [crossed out: fe] fett and put yn thes erbys yn them than take a chafyng dyche of colys and a dyche and put thes bages yn the dyche and spryng them with vynegyr and turne them and wend [? wond] them yn the dyche [crossed out: ty and ley them to hy fett as hot as he may suffyr and hyt and whyll the on is at hys fett lett the odyr warme yn the dyche
msItem.note: Added by a late 15th- or early 16th-century hand (the same hand that copied the preceding recipe)
Full transcription: deviates slightly from that by Mooney (1995) (e.g. see parbrak [probrak], tanfe [cause], lenthe [lerthe]).

foliation.p: Written in pencil in the upper right-hand corner of the recto of each leaf.

The unfoliated early modern paper flyleaves at the beginning and end of the manuscript have been allocated letters ([a]-[d]) and the unfoliated original parchment flyleaves at the beginning of the manuscript have been allocated numbers ([i]-[iv]) for reference purposes in this electronic catalogue record.

signatures.p: Leaf signatures in Roman numerals, usually cropped but sometimes still visible (see ff. 4r: IIII; f. 52r: [?]G IIII; f. 123r: P IIII.)

catchwords.seg: Catchwords in brown or red ink written in the lower right-hand corners of the last versos of quires; one in a decorative frame of brown ink (f. 8v).

supportDesc.condition: The lower margins of ff. 41-48, 65-84, and 88-95 are cut out.

layout.seg: Ruling in leadpoint, frames only. Single columns. 22-23 lines to the page, written above top line.

handNote.p: The manuscript has been largely (ff. 1r-124r) written by a single hand working in a cursive script with both anglicana, secretary features, and Bastarda. This script may also be described as a combination of Gothica Hybrida and Gothica Semihybrida.
Added texts and colophons in the hand of Henry Dingley in 1553 and 1557 (ff. [i] verso, 126r, and 127r) are in a hand with predominantly secretary and some anglicana features.
Folio features a poem added by a late 15th- or early 16th-century hand working in a secretary script.
Folios [iii] recto and [iv] recto feature a charm and medical recipes in late 15th- or early 16th-century hands working in cursive anglicana scripts.
Folio 124v features two medical recipes added by different late 15th- or early 16th-century hands working in a secretary script.
Folio 125r features two medical recipes addded by a late 15th- or early 16th-century hand working in a script with both anglicana and secretary features.

Folio 125v features an added medical recipe in a late 15th- or early 16th-century hand working in a hand with predominantly secretary and some anglicana features (it is different from that of Henry Dyngley).

decoNote.p: A full-page drawing of King Henry VI in dark ink (no colours) on f. [ii] verso: the king stands dressed in royal robe, holding a sceptre and wearing a crown, with, above him, a banderol that reads: henricus .vj. Rex anglie.
Cadels on ascenders of letters (typically initials) on the first lines of pages.
Headings of texts and individual recipes are rubricated with red ink.
Regular initials are sometimes fainly highlighted with yellow ink.
Headings of recipes are sometimes been underlined in red ink.

note.p: Notes towards a table of contents addded by a 17th-century hand to f. [ii] recto: Divers receits / De vrinis / De signis Zodiaci etcaetera / Anatomy . all perhaps by Henry Bingley.
Quire numbers (in Arabic numerals) added in pencil by a modern hand to the lower right-hand corners of the first rectos of quires.

binding.p: 18th- or 19th-century half white vellum binding with purple paper sides over pasteboards and 5 raised bands on the spine
Binding height: 225 mm; width: 160 mm; depth: 40 mm.

provenance.p: Henry Madhowsse [Maddows] (fl. 1475-1550) Madhowsse [Maddows], Henry, fl. 1475-1550: possible name of an owner or user whose first name is inscribed on f. 126v, Henri Madhowsse, in a late 15th- or early 16th-century hand. The same page and the next page (f. 127r) feature first names in similar hands: Thomas, Henri, and Andrew (f. 126v); and John S and Wylliam (f. 127r).

The name Burbage is inscribed in a late 15th- or early 16th-century hand on f. 127r and may be the family name of an owner or user of the manuscript. If so, then it may refer to the Burbage family of Leicestershire.

Henry Dingley (fl. 1553-1557) Dingley, Henry, fl. 1553-1557 century of Addington, Buckinghamshire: his full name inscribed by his own hand in colophons on f. [i] verso: Henri Dyngley Anno Christo 1553 Et Anno Philippi et Marie: primo et secundo vicessimo secundo die Marcij; f. 126r: Henry Dyngley Anno Christo 1557 Wrytten the xxx daye of Maye; and f. 127r: Henry Dyngley Anno Christo 1557 xxxj Maij of Adyngton in buckingegam scheree. Dingley added tracts on weights and measures (f. [i] verso) and a list of medicinal waters (f. 126r) to the manuscript.

John (?) Westall (fl. 17th century) (?) Westall, John, fl. 17th century: his full name inscribed by a 17th-century hand on f. 127r with their surname abbreviated as follows: Weall. A possible expansion is Westall. If correct, then he may have been John Westall, (c. 1585–1643) Westall, John, c. 1585–1643, bookbinder and -seller at Oxford who worked for the Bodleian Library from 1613 until 1641. However, this identification remains uncertain since no signature in his hand has been found for comparison with the name inscription in this manuscript.

One of the manuscripts of Thomas Gale (1635/6-1702) Gale, Thomas, 1635/6-1702, dean of York, antiquary and fellow of Trinity College Cambridge. The manuscript is listed in the list of Gale's manuscripts in Bernard, Catalogi librorum manuscriptorum Angliæ et Hiberniæ (1697).
One of the manuscripts of Roger Gale (1672-1744) Gale, Roger, 1672-1744, antiquary and scholar, son of Thomas Gale. Inherited from his father.

history.acquisition: Donated to Trinity College by Roger Gale (1672-1744)Gale, Roger, 1672-1744, son of Thomas Gale (1635/6-1702), in 1738. The alpha-numerical elements of its current classmark are printed on three labels pasted onto the spine (O.8.35), and those of its current and previous classmarks inscribed in brown ink on the inside of the front cover (O.8.35), ff. [ii] recto (C.3.7 [crossed out], O.14.37 [crossed out], and O.8.35), and its printed ex libris featuring its armorial coat of arms and name (Collegium SS. et Individuae Trinitatis in Academia Cantabrigiensi) pasted on f. [iv] verso.
